First impressions are important in a web environment, where users often scan a page briefly and make a decision about its usefulness in a matter of seconds. The four digital catalogues reviewed in the email survey have distinct designs, and one of the first questions for participants was if first glimpses of the catalogues&rsquo; homepages clearly conveyed the type of resource they were viewing. A strong majority of participants described the catalogues as &ldquo;scholarly/academic resources&rdquo; and &ldquo;educational resources.&rdquo;
 (participants could select more than one)     (participants could select more than one)    At first glance, participants were more likely to describe the catalogues as &ldquo;web pages&rdquo; than &ldquo;publications,&rdquo; which may say something about the perceived formality of these resources.
The AIC&rsquo;s Matisse catalogue is intentionally designed to resemble a book, and participants were therefore more likely to describe it as an &ldquo;ebook&rdquo; in their survey responses. The NGA&rsquo;s catalogue, in contrast, was more likely than the others to be described as a &ldquo;web page.&rdquo; Both of these findings align with focus group responses. Participants talked about the Matisse catalogue resembling a more static resource, similar to a book. Several also described the NGA homepage as &ldquo;old school web&rdquo; with its three-column layout and the large amount of information packed into the homepage.
